<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrabShortfall     09-24 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crab Shortfall,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Alaskan Crab Harvest May Put A Pinch On Diners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fishermen preparing to catch Alaska's
premium crab next week face a harvest projected to be 40 percent
below last year's, which could produce a quantum jump in prices and
put a pinch on restaurant owners.
   State biologists said they were surprised to discover data
showing a shortfall of red king crab after anticipating a
burgeoning harvest for the Bristol Bay fishing grounds this year.
They had projected a 20 percent to 30 percent increase in the 1988
haul over the 1987 take of 12.3 million pounds.
   But when the harvest opens Sunday, it will draw at least 200
boats competing for an estimated 7.5 million pounds of crab, said
Ken Griffin, an Alaska Department of Fish and Game biologist. The
harvest will likely last less than seven days, he said.
   The crab industry is $30 million business, Griffin said.
   Biologists suspect a variety of causes for the instability in
the population of the red king crab, which is available only off
the Alaska coast.
   The Bristol Bay fishing area, off Alaska's southwest coast,
yielded a peak harvest of 139 million pounds in 1980. But for
reasons still not understood, the crab population was decimated in
1982, and the fishery was not opened that year.
   The harvest that begins this weekend will be the year's major
catch of the seafood, which vies with cold-water lobster tails as a
premium item on restaurant menus in the United States and abroad.
   ``Demand is very strong both domestically and in Japan,'' said
John Martin, a shellfish promotion specialist for the Alaska
Seafood Marketing Institute.
   But a massive increase in prices could scare restaurateurs to
the point that they substitute less costly seafood as
top-of-the-line fare, Martin said.
   ``The best thing that's happened in the king crab business in
the last two years has been the stability of the prices,'' he said
Thursday.
   ``As long as we offer a high-quality product at competitive
prices, (red king crab) is very popular,'' he said. It brought $10
to $12 a pound wholesale in 1987.
   Brown and blue king crabs also are harvested off the Alaska
coast, but are valued less than their red cousin.
   Griffin said biologists don't know exactly why the supply
plunged. Influences that have been examined include interference
from bottomfishing, disease, increased water temperature and
harvests of undersized crab.
   Officials are combatting the harvest of the smaller crabs with a
state law requiring monitors to travel aboard vessels processing
crab at sea, where previously they had been been unable to observe
the catch. That law, similar to a federal measure for some of the
vessels in foreign fleets, requires observers to verify the
quantities and sizes of crab caught.
   But some fishermen balked at the law and unsuccessfully sought
an injunction to block the requirement for monitors. An attorney
for the Association of At-Sea Crab Processors said Thursday that
the refusal to grant the injunction this week was not appealed, and
processors were preparing to carry monitors.
   Attorney Mike Stanley of Juneau estimated that contractors who
provide the monitors will pass on about $9,000 in costs to each
processor required to use one.
</TEXT>
