<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Peace     09-24 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Peace,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Stumped By Cease-fire Deadlock</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Truce, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq claims it won the Persian Gulf war
with Iran, but officials increasingly suspect they are losing the
peace.
   A string of Iraqi battlefield victories this year devastated
Iran's war machine and apparently forced the Islamic Republic to
accept a U.N. cease-fire it had rejected for nearly a year.
   But Iraq's demand for a permanent settlement of the 8-year-old
conflict is stalled in U.N.-mediated peace talks. International
condemnation of Iraq's alleged use of outlawed chemical weapons
against Kurdish rebels has put the oountry on the diplomatic
defensive.
   ``The present situation is in Iran's favor, not Iraq's,''
Defense Minister Adnan Khairallah complained last week during a
news conference with foreign reporters last week. Diplomats agree.
   ``The only card they have on the Iranians is military advantage
... and how do they use it?'' one Western diplomat commented.
``They're in a dilemma.''
   Iraq claims Iran does not want peace, just a breathing space to
rebuild its army before resuming efforts to spread its Islamic
revolution.
   The no-peace, no-war situation also leaves Iraq unable to use
its only seaports _ deeply frustrating Iraqi rulers who have made
renewed shipping a priority.
   Iraqi suspicions were roused by Iran's wartime vows to spread
its fundamentalist revolution throughout the Moslem world and by
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's remark that accepting the cease-fire
was ``more deadly to me than poison.''
   Ironically, Iraq and its Arab allies demanded the U.N.
cease-fire measure when Iraq was on the defensive and Iranian
troops were hammering at the southern port city of Basra.
   Between April and July, Iraqi troops recaptured all the
territory they had lost to the Iranians over the previous six years
and even pushed into Iran. They claimed to have captured half of
Iran's tank force.
   Iraqi negotiators headed to the U.N.-sponsored peace talks in
Geneva vowing to negotiate on the basis of victory. But their
efforts to capitalize on military success has been frustrated.
   ``The Iranians have given nothing, absolutely zero'' at the
peace talks, the Western diplomat said.
   The talks have bogged down over Iraq's demand that its two
southern ports be put back in business immediately and that
sovereignty over the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, the southern border
between the two countries, be renegotiated.
   Silt and the hulks of half-sunken ships block both the ports at
Basra and Umm Qasr, which lies west of the Shatt-al-Arab, and the
political deadlock is delaying the lengthy task of clearing them.
   Khairallah said that leaves Iran free to use its other ports
further south down the gulf, while Iraq is deprived of its own, a
situation that leaves Iraq worse off than it was before the war
broke out in September 1980.
   President Saddam Hussein said recently that if Iraq cannot use
its ports, Iran should not be able to use its ports.
   Khairallah said that while renewed warfare was unlikely, if the
deadlock in talks persists, ``this might lead to fighting.''
   The cease-fire also gave Iraq a free hand against Kurdish
insurgents deprived of their Iranian ally.
   That Iraqi military operation against the Kurds succeeded, but
at the cost of rousing massive international condemnation of Iraq
over allegations it used chemical weapons.
   The criticism fueled Iraq's obsessive fear that the superpowers
and other nations will tilt their policies toward Iran, bolstering
its foe in future military or political clashes.
   The chemical weapons furor also threatens to torpedo improving
Iraqi relations with the United States and the West, which Iraq had
hoped can help rebuild it war-battered economy.
   Said one diplomat: ``They've just seen all that shot out from
under them.''
</TEXT>
