<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-88 1504EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-DemocratsText     09-24 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,920</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democrats' response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address:
   This is Dale Bumpers, senator from Arkansas.
   Democracy only works if people demand an accounting of those
elected officials in whom they have placed their trust, based on
their promises. If we allow ourselves to be deceived, allow our
attention to be diverted, or simply engage in the cynicism that
political promises aren't made to be kept anyway, then we all lose.
   You recall Ronald Reagan's big promise in 1980, that he would
double defense spending, cut taxes by 30 percent and balance the
budget _ a broken promise.
   In 1984 they said, ``It's morning in America'' and it sure is.
Every morning the U.S. Treasury has to print $575 million in new
money just for interest to keep the government afloat that day. And
if you don't remember anything else I say, remember this: The
deficit will be $150 billion this year and $135 billion of that is
just for interest on that part of the national debt added by this
administration.
   Now comes George Bush betting he can fool 51 percent of
America's voters until election day, that they won't know or care
that today's prosperity has come at an unbelievable burden to our
children.
   And he wants more debt. He says he wants billions more to deal
with the drug problems, and you and I agree that the drug problem is
   enormous. But when you ask him where the money's coming from, he
says, ``Read my lips _ no new taxes.''
   He wants billions more for defense, including Star Wars at a
possible cost of $1 trillion, but when you ask where the money's
coming from he says, ``Read my lips.''
   After this administration steadfastly opposed a day care bill
that would give working mothers the peace of mind that comes from
knowing their children are well cared for while they're at work,
George Bush read the polls, saw the gender gap and quickly proposed
his own $2 billion day care bill. And when asked where the money
was coming from he said, ``Read my lips.''
   He says he wants to be known as an education president yet you
will remember this administration wanted to make ketchup a
vegetable on school lunches, and vigorously attacked student loans
and grants that give less fortunate children an opportunity for a
college education.
   Now George Bush holds himself out as an environmentalist and
conservationist. But where was he while this administration
indulged James Watt's ``rape, ruin and run'' policies until he
became an unbearable political burden. This administration just
discovered acid rain three months ago. For George Bush to pose as
an environmentalist is like Bonnie and Clyde posing as bank
examiners.
   George Bush says judgment is everything in the Oval Office, and
Democrats agree wholeheartedly. So when this country was secretly
selling arms to the Ayatollah and cynically warning every other
nation not to; while we were trying to ransom hostages with arms
and telling the world we'd never deal with terrorists; George Bush
sat in the Oval Office _ absolutely mute so far as we know.
   And our question of George Bush is, why didn't he pound the
table like George Shultz and Cap Weinberger who called it a
cockamamie idea?
   There are 240 million people in the United States, and only five
or six people thought selling arms to the Ayatollah was a good
idea, and they all just happened to be in the White House at the
same time.
   George Bush said Thursday in Boston that he would be tough on
crime, but he couldn't even hear the shredders in the basement of
the White House when they were running at white hot speed.
Apparently his toughness on crime will depend on who's committing
the crime.
   And when he told us he was liberated and was now his own man,
and made his own very first, unfettered decision, he chose J.
Danforth Quayle as his running mate. And that decision speaks
volumes about his judgment.
   The people of this nation know we have problems, and they're not
afraid to face them. George Bush says elect me and I'll give you
more of the same: more debt, more tax relief for the rich, less
income for working people.
   Michael Dukakis says he believes that men and women should be
allowed the dignity of a decent job, an affordable home in which to
raise their families, a clean environment, oceans free of
unspeakable trash, an educational system that will get us out of
last place in international competition, health care for the
have-nots, an end to the nuclear arms race and the beginning of a
strong national defense in fact _ not one just where the only
criterion is how much money we spend on it; not one where we buy
weapons whether we need them or not, or whether they work or not.
   Never in our history has this nation needed so much leadership
and received so little.
   We can deal with every one of our problems. I agree with Barry
Goldwater when he says George Bush ought to talk about the issues.
No problem has ever been solved by ignoring it, and no nation has
ever achieved greatness by electing those who would divide us on
the issue of who loves America more. And we'll never make it by
continuing to elect those who break their promises.
   So we Democrats plead with you, America _ don't read their lips
_ look at their record.
</TEXT>
