<HEAD>Widespread Thunderstorms Over Southern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms erupted Saturday afternoon over northern Alabama
as showers ringed the Gulf Coast, but pleasant autumn weather
dominated from the Plains west to the Pacific Coast.
   Winds blew a tree onto a trailer near Madison, Ala., as low
pressure over northeast Arkansas moved slowly east and northeast
along a stationary front that extended from northeast Texas across
North Carolina.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered along the Gulf Coast
from southeast Texas into northwest Florida, from southeast
Missouri across southern Illinois and Ohio, and were widespread
from the middle and lower Mississippi Valley into the lower Ohio
and Tennessee valleys. The heaviest rainfall was over western and
central Tennessee where 1 to 1{ inches of rain was measured
Saturday morning.
   Southeast winds off the Atlantic Ocean were producing showers
and thunderstorm across extreme southern Florida.
   Hurricane Helene was slowing down as it turned northward over
the open waters of the Atlantic, its center 890 miles east of
Antigua with sustained winds at 115 mph.
   From the Plains west to the Pacific Coast, skies were mostly
sunny and afternoon temperatures were in the 60s or 70s. Clouds and
light rain were hitting parts of Washington state ahead of a cold
front over the Pacific Ocean.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 48
degrees at Olympia, Wash., and Arcata, Calif., to 94 degrees in
Florida at Orlando and Southwest Regional Airport in Fort Myers.
The low early Friday was 19 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Sunday's forecast called for widespread showers and
thunderstorms across the middle and southern Atlantic Coast regions
and inland across the central and southern Appalachians and in
parts of Upper Michigan. Widespread rain was expected over the
Pacific Northwest and the northern Plateau from a cold front
approaching from the west.
   High temperatures in the 70s or 80s were expected across much of
the nation. Highs in the 60s were forecast for the northern tier
from the northern Pacific Coast across the northern Plateau, the
northern rockies, the northern Plains, the northern Great Lakes
region and northern New England into the mid Atlantic Coast. Highs
in the low or mid 90s were forecast for the southern half of Texas
and the western Gulf Coast, southern Alabama, southern Georgia and
the northern half of Florida with mid or upper 90s expected in the
desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
